div.div:
Routers can share the same private gateway IP (like 192.168.1.1).
Only devices that are directly connected to the Internet are assigned unique public IPv4 addresses.
Under CGNAT, routers do not get public IPv4 addresses at all.
Your router doesn't "decide" its public IP; it asks the ISP for one
your router's WAN Public IPv4 is unique to your ISP's network
every internet-facing connection needs a globally unique source IP for correct routing and replies
